I have a laptop tech question that I hope one of the tech guys here can
name. I work on a T42 ThinkPad that has suffered from a screen problem for
10 months (I think the problem is with the connection between the screen and
computer rather than in the screen itself as the screen occasionally revives
at unpredictable moments).

As a result, I use a separate screen. So far I have been working on my
diningroom table with the laptop open and using the laptop keyboard. What I
want to do is buy a detached keyboard, fold the laptop up and put it under
my desk and put the keyboard, mouse and screen on the desk, getting my work
stuff off our table so we can use it to eat of of again.

The problem I need help with is that like virtually all laptops today this
one is set up with a physical switch that puts it into sleep mode when I
close the top. Is there a way in software to disarm that switch so that I
can run the laptop as if it were a desktop processor?

--
Bert Latamore
Freelance Writer/Photographer
ComputerWorld Online Columnist
</POST>
